    {
      "id": "topic29-lo-2",
      "front": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\">\n  <div style=\"font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; opacity: 0.85; margin-bottom: 10px; font-weight: 500;\">Learning Objective</div>\n  <div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.5;\">Name the critical enzyme required for CO2-transport, and its cellular location.</div>\n</div>"
      },
      "back": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\">\n  <div style=\"font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700;\">Critical enzyme required for CO2-transport, and...</div>\n</div><div style=\"background: #f8fafc; border-radius: 8px; padding: 12px 14px; margin-bottom: 14px; line-height: 1.6;\">\n  The critical enzyme required for carbon dioxide transport is <strong>carbonic anhydrase</strong>.\n</div><div style=\"display: grid; gap: 8px;\"><div style=\"padding-left: 12px; line-height: 1.5; border-left: 3px solid #e2e8f0;\">\n  It is primarily located in <strong>red blood cells</strong> where it catalyzes rapid conversion of CO₂ and water to carbonic acid, which dissociates into <strong>bicarbonate</strong> ions and hydrogen ions.\n</div><div style=\"padding-left: 12px; line-height: 1.5; border-left: 3px solid #e2e8f0;\">\n  This speeds the reaction approximately <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">10,000-fold</span>.\n</div><div style=\"padding-left: 12px; line-height: 1.5; border-left: 3px solid #e2e8f0;\">\n  <strong>Carbonic anhydrase</strong> is also found in renal tubules and various epithelial cells where it regulates pH and <strong>bicarbonate</strong> handling.\n</div></div>"
      },
      "tags": [
        "carbondioxide",
